## Best Practices

### Use Clear, Action-Oriented Titles

Write step titles that describe the action users will take.

<CardGroup cols={2}>
<Card title="Good" icon="check">
```markdown
<Step title="Install Dependencies">
<Step title="Configure Environment Variables">
<Step title="Deploy to Production">
```
</Card>

<Card title="Avoid" icon="x">
```markdown
<Step title="Dependencies">
<Step title="Environment">
<Step title="Production">
```
</Card>
</CardGroup>

### Include Verification Steps

Help users confirm they completed the step correctly.

```markdown
<Step title="Start the Development Server">
Run the development server:

\`\`\`bash
npm run dev
\`\`\`

<Callout type="success">
Verify the server started by visiting http://localhost:3000
</Callout>
</Step>
```

### Provide Context Before Code

Explain what the code does before showing it.

```markdown
<Step title="Create API Client">
Create a reusable API client that handles authentication and error handling:

<CodeSnippet language="typescript" title="lib/api-client.ts">
{`// Implementation here`}
</CodeSnippet>
</Step>
```

### Highlight Critical Lines

Use the `highlight` attribute to draw attention to important code sections.

<CodeSnippet language="javascript" highlight="4-6">
{`function fetchData() {
  const response = await fetch('/api/data')
  
  if (!response.ok) {
    throw new Error('Failed to fetch data')
  }
  
  return response.json()
}`}
</CodeSnippet>

### Limit Step Count

Break procedures with more than 7-8 steps into multiple sections or use accordions for optional steps.

## When to Use Steps

<CardGroup cols={2}>
<Card title="Use Steps For" icon="check">
- Installation procedures
- Configuration workflows
- Tutorial sequences
- Setup guides
- Migration instructions
- Multi-stage deployments
</Card>

<Card title="Use Other Components For" icon="lightbulb">
- Platform-specific instructions (use Tabs)
- Optional configuration (use Accordions)
- Reference documentation (use ParameterField)
- Conceptual explanations (use standard text)
</Card>
